      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: Because of a court ruling favorable to them, members of the Ku Klux Klan today donned hoods for their annual Labor Day rally in Georgia. It was the first opportunity since 1951 that they could do so without the threat of police intervention.</p>
        <p>Because of a court ruling favorable to them, members of the Ku Klux Klan today donned hoods for their annual Labor Day rally in Georgia. It was the first opportunity since 1951 that they could do so without the threat of police intervention.</p>
        <p>About 40 of the 100 participants wore robes and open-face hoods and 15 wore hoods covering their faces in the march through this northeastern Georgia city. They held a 40-minute rally at the Hall County Courthouse and then dispersed.</p>
        <p>Members said the gathering was held, in part, to acknowledge victory in the overturning of a 1951 state law that prohibits concealment of identity in public places.</p>
      </block>
